<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-06-25T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-06-25T10:00:00-05:00" n="651" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d651">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">711.544/17: Telegram (part air)</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Bern</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-06-25T16:00:00+01:00">June 25, 1935—4
                                    p.m.</date><lb/>[Received June 27—5:06 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>28. Department’s 45, June 22, 3 p.m. The Foreign Office states that
                                in its opinion article 52 of the Constitution does not give it the
                                right to conclude an international convention depriving Swiss
                                citizens of their nationality. It is preparing a counter-draft
                                looking towards the solution of this matter.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>